      "text": "Commonwealth Edison Company Supplemental Statement Revised General Terms and Conditions June 23, 2025\n\nSUPPLEMENTAL STATEMENT ELECTRICITY ILL. C. C. No. 10\n\nGeneral Terms and Conditions: \n7th Revised Sheet No. 125 canceling 6th Revised Sheet No. 125 \n6th Revised Sheet No. 127 canceling 5th Revised Sheet No. 127 \nOriginal Sheet No. 127.1 \n7th Revised Sheet No. 129 canceling 6th Revised Sheet No. 129 \n1st Revised Sheet No. 149.2 canceling Original Sheet No. 149.2 \nOriginal Sheet No. 149.3 \n2nd Revised Sheet No. 150 canceling 1st Revised Sheet No. 150 \nOriginal Sheet No. 150.1 \n4th Revised Sheet No. 151 canceling 3rd Revised Sheet No. 151 \n1st Revised Sheet No. 151.3 canceling Original Sheet No. 151.3 \nFiled with the Illinois Commerce Commission on June 23, 2025 \nWith this filing, Commonwealth Edison Company (Company or ComEd) proposes several \nrevisions to its General Terms and Conditions (GT&C) tariff to help ensure that new \nservice requests of Large Demand Project Applicants and Customers neither harm, nor \nunjustly shift costs to, other customers. These revisions promote that goal by providing for \ndeposits or security to ensure recovery of engineering costs associated with these \napplications; by facilitating the procurement of long lead materials required for requested \nservice without imposition of acquisition cost and risk on other customers; and by \nmemorializing in ComEd’s retail tariffs its practice of ensuring, through Federal Energy \nRegulatory Commission (FERC)-jurisdictional rates, that large load customers in fact make \na contribution to the transmission revenue requirement commensurate with their requests \nfor service. In addition, these modifications memorialize ComEd’s practice of conducting \ncoordinated analyses of transmission and distribution system impacts of “clusters” to \napplicants through joint studies, reducing costs and increasing the speed and efficiency of \nthe process. Thus, these tariff revisions both memorialize existing practices and provide \nfor process improvements. \nGT&C Revisions Related to Definitions \nThe proposed revisions memorialize and improve ComEd’s existing definitions and define \nthe types of large load customers to which deposit and security processes apply. The \nrevisions define a Large Demand Project Applicant or Customer as a customer requesting \nrevised or new service that will be equal to or over 50 MW in ten calendar years of service. \nAdditionally, the requirements of an Acceptable Letter of Credit (LOC), which under some \n\nCommonwealth Edison Company Supplemental Statement Revised General Terms and Conditions June 23, 2025\n\nconditions substitute for a cash deposit, are memorialized in the Definitions section of \nGT&C. \nGT&C Revisions Related to the Deposit Requirements for Large Demand Projects \nThe following proposed revisions memorialize and improve ComEd’s existing practices. \nComEd is proposing to revise GT&C to require a Large Demand Project Applicant or \nCustomer to provide the Company with a projected load ramp extending through the first \nten (10) calendar years that the project will be in service. The projected load ramp shall \ninclude monthly projections of the applicant’s or customer’s Maximum Kilowatts Delivered \n(MKD). If the applicant or customer revises the projected load ramp before the Company \nhas completed engineering analysis of the project, then the Company, at its sole \ndiscretion, may initiate a new engineering analysis. A Large Demand Project Applicant or \ncustomer must pay the Company the costs of the initial engineering analysis as a condition \nfor the Company commencing the new engineering analysis. Providing an annual load \nramp is critical because without it ComEd cannot accurately determine the facilities \nrequired for service and the expected service date and, moreover, may not be able to \naccurately determine the facility requirements and service dates of other customers whose \nstudies take as an input the load of other customers. \nThe proposed revisions provide that the Company shall conduct an initial engineering \nanalysis of the facilities needed to provide electric service to a Large Demand Project \nApplicant or Customer, as it does now, but also clarify that the Company may, in its sole \ndiscretion, conduct such analysis with its engineering analysis of the facilities needed to \nprovide electric service to one or more other Large Demand Project Applicants or \nCustomers. Such a combined analysis (a Cluster Study) may analyze the impact that the \nincluded applications or requests would collectively have on the transmission system and \non the Company’s distribution system and identify transmission and / or distribution system \nreinforcements and / or expansions needed to ensure the safety, adequacy, reliability, and \nefficiency of those systems and the Company’s ability to serve all of its customers. \nCurrently, the Company anticipates continuing to use Cluster Studies, as they are the most \ncost-effective, expeditious, and robust means of studying a high volume of large load \nrequests. If an Applicant’s application or a Customer’s request is the subject of a Cluster \nStudy, then each Applicant or Customer is responsible for an equal share of the total \nactual cost of the Cluster Study. The Cluster Study does not replace or supplant the need \nto conduct additional analyses prior to the commencement of service and does not alter or \nlimit the Applicant’s or Customer’s responsibility for the Company’s costs of such analyses. \nFinally, ComEd is proposing to amend GT&C to require that a Large Demand Project \nApplicant or Customer provide a deposit sufficient to secure the costs of procurement of \nlong lead materials required for the Applicant’s or Customer’s project, as determined by \nthe Company. Such deposit, less any amount retained by the Company under Rider NS – \nNonstandard Services and Facilities or other applicable rate, shall be refunded upon \ncommencement of permanent service and the submission of any deposit under Rider DE - \n\n| | Commonwealth Edison Company | | |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| | Supplemental Statement | | |\n| | Revised General Terms and Conditions | | |\n| | June 23, 2025 | | |\n\nDistribution System Extensions. In the absence of such deposits, the acquisition of such \nequipment would increase the costs of service to all customers. \nGT&C Revisions for the Amount and Refunding Deposits for Large Demand Projects \nComEd is proposing to amend GT&C to clarify that a Large Demand Project Applicant or \nCustomer is required to provide a security for the Company’s analysis and engineering \ncosts. This security shall consist of a deposit calculated based on the maximum MKD \nincluded in the load ramp provided by the Applicant or Customer and shall be the sum of \n$1,000,000 plus $500,000 for each additional whole 100 MW of MKD above 200 MW. If \nthe amount of the deposit exceeds $2,000,000, then for the incremental amount greater \nthan $2,000,000, the customer must also provide the Company with an Acceptable LOC in \nthe amount over $2,000,000. This revision reflects both the fact that costs of engineering \nstudies increase with the size and complexity of the project and the fact that larger projects \nconsume a comparatively greater share of limited engineering resources. \nAt the earlier of the commencement of service or the posting of the deposit under Rider DE \n- Distribution System Extensions, the Company shall refund the deposit and, if applicable, \nrelease the Acceptable LOC less the sum of: (a) the Customer’s or Applicant’s share of the \ncost of Cluster Study, (b) the cost of actual non-standard engineering costs attributable to \nthe Applicant’s or Customer’s project, and (c) the cost of any other actual engineering \ncosts attributable to an Applicant’s or Customer’s project that is cancelled. This provision \ndoes not limit or replace any other requirements to provide deposits or post security \nauthorized by the Company’s Schedule of Rates or other ",
